ram":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xEwFsBDAa1wFoqBjJgewFdiAXEAIyoA2VYk1wBKNCCk4CJMpgDuhLgAtsAJyoKQVCh24SpR8oXzkAfAF4+g4aJ17OXQ8eOZeuAOYlyAZ1xcAIQ2QiLy9CF2ZLr6zi6uCUb8oaLxiVIARBDEvuz4REyEuNwg+JzYvhli8TJEpOR4AA6svsoOsWnS-kGRYeQA1L32MU7Vkq7JUTV4dfLYhL6NVFxMKiAUneRsxNjkmLgAjgD86yAA5EqqGlpiIJdqmgqbCZj7x6dnTS3Kt1+tzuN0tJcAJ-ORcOp1Kx1CAMgBVYg0YisBTEEDqQ7sXC+HgRCIAWQAggBpACi9EJUCgAHk4QA5AAqGUBQMSG2q8Xmi2WqwkWBmch0LAATORqHRGCxYiBkAAGWXVIA","body":"(define acc2 (make-account 100)) "},{"body":"\n    will produce a completely separate account object, which maintains its\n    own local ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"balance"},{"body":".\n  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.1","id":"#ex-3.1","child":[{"body":"\n    An \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"accumulator","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":" is a\n    procedure\n    that is called repeatedly with a single numeric argument and accumulates its\n    arguments into a sum. Each time it is called, it returns the currently\n    accumulated sum. Write a\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"make-accumulator"},{"body":"\n    that generates accumulators, each maintaining an independent sum.  The\n    input to \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"make-accumulator"},{"body":"\n    should specify the initial value of the sum; for example\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":22,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEERMBbAQwGtcBaWgY1YFdqOAbWgFwD2AJxABWAJQSgA","body":"(define A (make-accumulator 5)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":23,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEERMBbAQwGtcBaWgY1YFdqOAbWgFwD2AJxABWAJQSMmSsgAMEoA","body":"(A 10) ","output":"15"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":24,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEERMBbAQwGtcBaWgY1YFdqOAbWgFwD2AJxABWAJQSMmSsgAM0rHMVA","body":"(A 10) ","output":"25"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":25,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.2","id":"#ex-3.2","child":[{"body":"\n    In software-testing applications, it is useful to be able to count the\n    number of times a given\n    procedure\n    is called during the course of a computation.  Write a\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"make-monitored"},{"body":"\n    that takes as input a\n    procedure,","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"f"},{"body":", that itself takes one input.  The result\n    returned by \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"make-monitored"},{"body":"\n    is a third\n    procedure,\n    say ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"mf"},{"body":", that keeps track of the number of times\n    it has been called by maintaining an internal counter. If the input to\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"mf"},{"body":" is the\n    special symbol ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"how-many-calls"},{"body":",\n      \n    then ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"mf"},{"body":" returns the value of the counter.  If\n    the input is the \n    special symbol ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"reset-count"},{"body":",\n    then ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"mf"},{"body":" resets the counter to zero.  For any\n    other input, ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"mf"},{"body":" returns the result of calling\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"f"},{"body":" on that input and increments the counter.\n    For instance, we could make a monitored version of the\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"sqrt"},{"body":"procedure:","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":26,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAGcRMBbAQwGtcBaage2MIBdWAnXbCgEcenAJSigA","body":"(define s (make-monitored sqrt)) "},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":27,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAGcRMBbAQwGtcBaage2MIBdWAnXbCgEcenAJSiMmSsgAMM0UA","body":"(s 100) ","output":"10"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":28,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAGcRMBbAQwGtcBaage2MIBdWAnXbCgEcenAJSiMmSsgAMMiVkoByABasA7i1rEAnkwDGtADZHyAflFA","body":"(s 'how-many-calls?) ","output":"1"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":29,"eval":false},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":30,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.3","id":"#ex-3.3","child":[{"body":"\n    Modify the \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"make-account"},{"body":"procedure\n    so that it creates\n    \n    password-protected accounts.  That is, \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"make-account"},{"body":"\n    should take a\n    symbol\n    as an additional argument, as in\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":31,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMBjSkTAW3IGtcBaKygewFdiAXEZAAZBIAOQBnXJQBOuXiwAO5ceIDuHadgCUWoA","body":"(define acc (make-account 100 'secret-password)) "},{"body":"\n    The resulting account object should process a request only if it is\n    accompanied by the password with which the account was created, and\n    should otherwise return a complaint:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":32,"eval":true,"prependLength":3,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMBjSkTAW3IGtcBaKygewFdiAXEZAAZBIAOQBnXJQBOuXiwAO5ceIDuHadgCUWjJkzsxkmXMXK1G7GNWFeAC2zTyqrSAAsgrUA","body":"((acc 'secret-password 'withdraw) 40) ","output":"60"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":33,"eval":true,"prependLength":5,"program":"chap=3&prgrm=NwAgygkgwgCiDMA6AjCgUGgFAEwKYDMBLAO1xAEMBjSkTAW3IGtcBaKygewFdiAXEZAAZBIAOQBnXJQBOuXiwAO5ceIDuHadgCUWjJkzsxkmXMXK1G7GNWFeAC2zTyqrSAAsg3VgPUjHOqwc9rjSZirqmmJ4Chzitq4ArJ5AA","body":"((acc 'some-other-password 'deposit) 50) ","output":"\"Incorrect password\""}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":34,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"EXERCISE","title":"Exercise 3.4","id":"#ex-3.4","child":[{"body":"\n    Modify the \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"make-account"},{"body":"procedure\n    of exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.3","href":"/sicp/3.1.1#ex-3.3"},{"body":" by adding another\n    local state variable so that, if an account is accessed more than seven\n    consecutive times with an incorrect password, it invokes the\n    procedure","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"call-the-cops"},{"body":".","tag":"#text"}],"solution":[{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":35,"eval":false}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-1","count":1,"href":"/sicp/3.1.1#footnote-link-1","child":[{"body":"Actually, this is not quite true. One exception was the \n    \n    random-number generator\n    in section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"1.2.6","href":"/sicp/1.2.6"},{"body":".  Another exception\n    involved the\n    \n    operation/type tables we introduced in\n    section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.4.3","href":"/sicp/2.4.3"},{"body":", where the values of two\n    calls to ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"get"},{"body":" with the same arguments\n    depended on intervening calls to ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"put"},{"body":".\n    On the other hand, until we introduce assignment, we have no way to\n    create such\n    procedures\n    ourselves.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-2","count":2,"href":"/sicp/3.1.1#footnote-link-2","child":[{"body":"\n\tThe value of a ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set!"},{"body":" expression is\n\timplementation-dependent. ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"Set!"},{"body":" should be\n\tused only for its effect, not for its value.\n\t \n\tThe name ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"set!"},{"body":" reflects a naming convention\n\tused in Scheme: Operations that change the values of variables (or that\n\tchange data structures, as we will see in\n\tsection ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.3","href":"/sicp/3.3"},{"body":") are given names that end\n\twith an exclamation point.  This is similar to the convention of\n\tdesignating predicates by names that end with a question mark.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-3","count":3,"href":"/sicp/3.1.1#footnote-link-3","child":[{"body":"We have already used \n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":" and in \n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"begin"},{"body":" implicitly in our programs, because in\n\tScheme the body of a procedure can be a sequence of expressions.  Also,\n\tthe ","tag":"#text"},{"body":"consequent","tag":"LATEX"},{"body":" part of each clause in a\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"cond"},{"body":" expression can be a sequence of\n\texpressions rather than a single expression.","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-4","count":4,"href":"/sicp/3.1.1#footnote-link-4","child":[{"body":"In programming-language jargon, the variable\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"balance"},{"body":" is said to be \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"encapsulated","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":" within the\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"new-withdraw"},{"body":"\n        procedure. Encapsulation reflects the general system-design principle\n\tknown as the \n        ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"hiding principle","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":": One can make a system more modular and robust\n\tby protecting parts of the system from each other; that is, by providing\n\tinformation access only to those parts of the system that have a\n\t\"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"need to know.","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\"","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-5","count":5,"href":"/sicp/3.1.1#footnote-link-5","child":[{"body":"\n    In contrast with\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"new-withdraw"},{"body":"\n    above, we do not have to use\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"let"},{"body":"\n    to make ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SCHEMEINLINE","body":"balance"},{"body":" a local variable, since\n    formal\n    parameters are already\n    local. This will be clearer after the discussion of the environment\n    model of evaluation in\n    section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.2","href":"/sicp/3.2"},{"body":".\n    (See also\n    exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"3.10","href":"/sicp/3.2.3#ex-3.10"},{"body":".)","tag":"#text"}]}]